Title:
Bypassing static analysis – Deep Dive

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post breaks down how AV/EDR static scanning evaluates files when they land on disk, focusing on hashes, byte signatures, suspicious strings/IAT imports, and PE section entropy.  
- It demonstrates a practical workflow for signature evasion: use ThreatCheck to identify flagged byte sequences, then reverse in Ghidra to locate the responsible code/constant and modify implementation details without changing behavior (example: altering AES routines in a Havoc payload).  
- It covers packing as an alternative (PEzor + donut), including tradeoffs like packer templates being signatured and environment-bound decryption (e.g., using GetComputerNameExA/FQDN).  
- The author then builds custom shellcode loaders (stageless and staged), showing how encrypting embedded shellcode (AES) defeats simple signature matching but can raise entropy-based flags.  
- It also highlights static detection via suspicious imports and shows API hashing to remove obvious WinAPI names from the IAT/strings while still resolving functions at runtime.  
- Overall, it’s most useful for red teamers/pentesters and malware developers who need to understand and iterate on disk-based evasion, and for defenders who want to recognize these evasion patterns and their artifacts.

Technical Focus:
- AV/EDR static detection primitives (hashes, signatures, strings/IAT, entropy)
- Signature breaking via reverse engineering (ThreatCheck + Ghidra)
- Packing and PIC shellcode conversion (PEzor, donut)
- Windows shellcode loader patterns (VirtualAlloc/memcpy/VirtualProtect/CreateThread)
- Payload encryption (XOR vs AES) and entropy side-effects
- API hashing / runtime API resolution from exports (kernel32.dll)

Use Cases:
- Iteratively modifying payloads to evade Defender/AV static signatures on disk
- Identifying which code/bytes/constants trigger detections and patching them safely
- Building custom staged/stageless loaders with encrypted payload handling
- Reducing static indicators by removing suspicious imports via API hashing
- Evaluating packed/encrypted binaries for entropy-based detection risk

Keywords:
static analysis, antivirus, EDR, Windows Defender, signature-based detection, MD5, ThreatCheck, Ghidra, PE file, Import Address Table, IAT, entropy analysis, Detect It Easy, PE-bear, Havoc C2, PEzor, donut, shellcode loader, VirtualAlloc, VirtualProtect, CreateThread, WaitForSingleObject, API hashing, kernel32.dll exports, GetComputerNameExA, AES encryption, XOR, staged payload, stageless payload, msfvenom, Meterpreter